04624nam a22006855i 9781501745348DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20191995nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017453487 a10.7591/97815017453482doi  a(DE-B1597)534330  a(OCoLC)1114890462  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aPOL0240002bisacsh04a3372221 aWebb, Michael C., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Political Economy of Policy Coordination :bInternational Adjustment since 1945 /cMichael C. Webb. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2019] 4c©1995  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCornell Studies in Political Economy00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1. Coordinating Macroeconomic Adjustment Policy -- t2. The Structure of the International System and Patterns of Policy Coordination -- t3. Insulation and Symptom Management, 1945-55 -- t4. Symptom Management, 1956-70 -- t5. Flexible Exchange Rates and the Search for Policy Autonomy, 1971-77 -- t6. Macroeconomic Conflict and Coordination, 1978-94 -- t7. Conclusions: International Structures, Domestic Politics and Policy Coordination -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMichael C. Webb explores a central question about postwar economic history: how has the growth of international markets affected the coordination of economic policy among nations? His analysis overturns the popular assumption that policy coordination has eroded as American hegemony has receded. Instead, he argues that the growing mobility of capital forced governments to abandon the strategies they had used in the 1950s and 60s to insulate monetary and fiscal policies from international influences, and to move toward more direct coordination of central economic strategies.Webb shows that since 1945 there has been a crucial shift in the pattern of international collaboration. He focuses on three types of adjustment policy: trade and capital controls, balance-of-payment lending and intervention in foreign-exchange markets, and monetary and fiscal policies. Noting that the first two types are no longer effective, he demonstrates that governments now rely more on monetary and fiscal policy coordination to regulate the global economy.As the expansion of international finance created greater turbulence in the global economy in the 1980s, the liberal system of international trade threatened to collapse. Webb examines in particular how the United States, Japan, and Germany took unprecedented steps to coordinate monetary and fiscal policies in the late 1980s and early 1990s, although domestic political obstacles—not any decline in U.S. power—limited the impact of this policy coordination. He concludes by assessing the effectiveness of these attempts to reconcile the goal of a stronger liberal system of economic exchange with the desire to maintain national autonomy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 4aGeneral Economics. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Economic Policy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Archive Pre-2000z978311053617140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150174534840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501745348423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501745348/original  a978-3-11-053617-1  Cornell University Press Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK